04126nam a22006495i 9780674274358DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222006mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742743587 a10.4159/97806742743582doi  a(DE-B1597)613853  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aCB251b.K38 2006eb 7aPOL0120002bisacsh04a909/.097670832231 aKepel, Gilles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe War for Muslim Minds :bIslam and the West /cGilles Kepel. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMap -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Failure of the Oslo Peace -- t2 The Neoconservative Revolution -- t3 Striking at the Faraway Enemy -- t4 Al Qaeda’s Resilience -- t5 Saudi Arabia in the Eye of the Storm -- t6 The Calamity of Nation-Building in Iraq -- t7 The Battle for Europe -- tConclusion -- tSources -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe events of September 11, 2001, forever changed the world as we knew it. In their wake, the quest for international order has prompted a reshuffling of global aims and priorities. In a fresh approach, Gilles Kepel focuses on the Middle East as a nexus of international disorder and decodes the complex language of war, propaganda, and terrorism that holds the region in its thrall. The breakdown of the Israeli-Palestinian peace process in 2000 was the first turn in a downward spiral of violence and retribution. Meanwhile, a neo-conservative revolution in Washington unsettled U.S. Mideast policy, which traditionally rested on the twin pillars of Israeli security and access to Gulf oil. In Saudi Arabia and Afghanistan, a transformation of the radical Islamist doctrine of Bin Laden and Zawahiri relocated the arena of terrorist action from Muslim lands to the West; Islamist radicals proclaimed jihad against their enemies worldwide. Kepel examines the impact of global terrorism and the ensuing military operations to stem its tide. He questions the United States' ability to address the Middle East challenge with Cold War rhetoric, while revealing the fault lines in terrorist ideology and tactics. Finally, he proposes the way out of the Middle East quagmire that triangulates the interests of Islamists, the West, and the Arab and Muslim ruling elites. Kepel delineates the conditions for the acceptance of Israel, for the democratization of Islamist and Arab societies, and for winning the minds and hearts of Muslims in the West.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aEast and West. 0aIslamy21st century. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh1 aGhazaleh, Pascale.40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674274358zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674274358423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674274358/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK